<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'SOAPDISH' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This spirited 1991 comedy turns upon the amusing notion that the stars of TV 
soap operas have lives as screwed up and crazy as those of the characters they 
play, if not more so. Presiding over the long-running soap in question, "The 
Sun Also Sets," is America's sweetheart (Sally Field), who at 42 is beginning 
to wonder if there's more to life than tearfully saying such lines as, "I'm 
guilty of love -- guilty of love in the first-degree." Watching Kevin Kline (as 
her lecherous old flame), arguably the supreme farceur of his generation, meet 
his match in Field is very much of a treat (Cinemax, Sunday at 6:15 p.m.; 
Friday at 10:30 a.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
