<HEADLINE>
<P>
TREK TALK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When Steven Lynn faults the makers of "Star Trek" for creating non-human 
civilizations that "are imbued with evil qualities right out of a textbook on 
racial stereotypes and prejudice" (Letters, Nov. 27), I can only conclude that 
he has been half-asleep when watching "Star Trek: The Next Generation" and its 
spinoff, "Deep Space Nine." 
</P>
<P>
 Contrary to his observations, one of the most interesting developments of this 
long-running humanist morality play is the evolution of the aliens through the 
seven years of the series.Though each of the various antagonistic interstellar 
species begins as a race of undifferentiated comic-book villains, as the series 
progress, multidimensional individuals emerge, often as characters who garner 
our sympathy. 
</P>
<P>
 C. J. WRIGHT 
</P>
<P>
 Venice 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 There are plenty of alien races on the show that aren't depicted as (take your 
pick) warlike, inferior, impolite or indecent. If Lynn had the brains that God 
gave a Tribble, he would see the depth and humanity given to the Cardassians, 
the Klingons, the Romulans, etc. (and yes, even the Borg) by the producers and 
staff of all the shows, old and new. 
</P>
<P>
 P.S. It's Trill , not Thrill. 
</P>
<P>
 ROD RUSSELL 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 A Calendar gremlin was responsible for that typo, not reader Lynn.  
</P>
