<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRIBE COULD GROW ALONG WITH CASINO; GAMBLING: THE MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT INDIANS 
OPENED THE FOXWOODS HIGH STAKES BINGO AND CASINO IN LEDYARD, CONN., IN 1992. 
SINCE THEN, PEQUOTS HAVE BEEN POPPING UP ALL OVER TO CLAIM THEIR SHARE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL DERMODY, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Suddenly, there are a lot more Narragansett Indians -- and not because of more 
babies or fewer deaths, or because new aboriginal villages have been discovered 
in the wilds of Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
 The reason: Since the tribe announced plans to open a casino that could 
produce hundreds of millions of dollars annually, would-be Narragansetts have 
come out of the woodwork. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wouldn't say we're inundated, but we are seeing more come forward," said 
Ella Sekatau, the tribe's medicine woman and genealogist. 
</P>
<P>
 "Some are definitely not Narragansett, but we'll have to expect some liars and 
cheats when we're living in a country where God is green." 
</P>
<P>
 It's something the Mashantucket Pequot Indians have learned already. Since 
1992, when the tribe opened its Foxwoods High Stakes Bingo and Casino in 
Ledyard, Conn., Pequots have been popping up all over. 
</P>
<P>
 "We get about eight to 10 people a week coming in here saying they think 
they've got some Indian blood in them," said Joey Carter, a Pequot. "Some of 
them aren't even close. Everybody wants a piece of the pie. We're the rich 
little Indians." 
</P>
<P>
 The Foxwoods casino was expected to take in $800 million in 1994. And in 1995, 
Connecticut officials expect revenues to hit $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
 There are only about 300 Pequots -- 50 to 75 previously unknown members have 
been located since the casino opened -- and each gets a portion of the take. 
</P>
<P>
 The amount of the share depends on the size of a family and the age of the 
Indian. For instance, tribal elders get an increased share, according to a 
distribution plan filed with the federal Indian Gaming Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 Carter, who is married with three boys and a baby on the way, said his share 
for 1994 would be between $85,000 and $160,000, depending on actual casino 
profits. That's on top of his salary for working at the casino -- something 
every Pequot must do to qualify for a share -- and his wife's income. 
</P>
<P>
 "The real millionaires will be the children, who get their share every year 
from birth and will have quite a lot built up by the time they're 21," Carter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Carter said he's gotten calls from people as far away as England. Women have 
called inquiring about eligible Indian men. They've even asked about the 
consequences of getting pregnant on the reservation, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "They call the unmarried men 'The Elite Few,' " Carter said. "We have to tell 
them to watch out, especially the ones coming of age. There are people out 
there who would do things for money." 
</P>
<P>
 Under tribal rules, applicants may be accepted only if they have at least 
one-sixteenth Pequot blood and are descended from one of five sisters who lived 
on the 200-acre reservation around 1900 -- the last pure-blood Pequots. 
</P>
<P>
 The Narragansetts also go back about 100 years to define themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 When English colonist Roger Williams came to Rhode Island in 1636, there were 
about 100,000 Narragansetts, the largest tribe in southern New England. 
Disease, war and other factors reduced that number. 
</P>
<P>
 All existing Narragansetts trace their heritage to a list of 324 people living 
on the tribe's Charlestown reservation in 1881. The list was created by the 
state's General Assembly, which decided in 1880 to put up for sale all but two 
acres of the reservation and pay those living on the land $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
 The plan was to eliminate the Narragansetts as a nation. Instead, it may have 
ensured their survival. 
</P>
<P>
 "To be a tribal member, you must trace your ancestors to that list," 
Narragansett first tribal member Matthew Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
 Even in 1881, most Narragansetts weren't full-blooded. Many had married whites 
or blacks and, over time, their ancestors' Indian blood has thinned. 
</P>
<P>
 "They labeled us black, mulatto, coppers, Negroes, anything that would further 
the goal of genocide," said Sekatau, the medicine woman. 
</P>
<P>
 Flash forward more than a century, and hear developer Donald Trump complain to 
Congress about the special advantages given to Indian-operated casinos like 
Foxwoods. He points out that its operators are far from full-blooded. 
</P>
<P>
 But federal officials say that isn't their concern. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't look at whether tribe members descend from full-blooded Indians," 
said Holly Reckord of the Bureau of Indian Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
 Though the Narragansetts have converted to Christianity and lost much of their 
culture, they remain a political unit as defined by the federal government. 
Every year, a Thanksgiving festival is held on the tribal land. The tribe also 
has a council of leaders and a church. 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Lathel Duffield, chief of the bureau's Tribal Enrollment Branch, said many 
people make the mistake of believing today's Indians should look and act like 
Indians of old. 
</P>
<P>
 "How could Indians remain aboriginal in a modern world?" he asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
