<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEN. THOMAS KUCHEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thank you for providing front-page coverage to the sensitive obituary by 
Kenneth Reich on Sen. Thomas Kuchel (Nov. 23). In the arena of today's 
political circus, it is easy to forget that our nation occasionally produces 
representatives of true heroic proportion.Perhaps increased media focus on 
these few individuals of unwavering principle would help us view the future 
with more optimism. 
</P>
<P>
 I have registered with party selection only once, and that for the privilege 
of supporting Kuchel in his primary race against Max Rafferty. Although always 
thereafter a "decline to state," I have considered myself a "Kuchel Republican" 
at heart. 
</P>
<P>
 RONALD SEGALL 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 * As a lifelong liberal, I have often been asked by co-workers if I have ever 
voted for a Republican. I have always answered that, yes, I did vote Republican 
once. That vote was for Kuchel, who I considered a principled man who stood for 
something. That those younger colleagues say "Thomas who?" only indicates how 
long it's been since there was a Republican who deserved my vote. 
</P>
<P>
 Your excellent obituary confirmed my belief that he truly earned my 
confidence. 
</P>
<P>
 ROBERT S. HELFMAN 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
