<HEADLINE>
<P>
WRITER CLARIFIES HER OPTIMA COVERAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This is to correct an error and to give credit where credit is due. The error 
was in a letter of mine about the county program OPTIMA, which you printed Nov. 
20. What I said in the letter was based upon misinformation gleaned while 
talking with OPTIMA. 
</P>
<P>
 Credit is due to Supervisor Harriett M. Wieder. Even though I do not live in 
her district, her office phoned me, asking if I had talked with OPTIMA. When I 
told Wieder's assistant that OPTIMA was where I had gotten my information, she 
told me that existing patient-doctor relationships will be continued and that 
there will be no problem about repeat visits for my ongoing conditions. She 
also said that, although nothing has been decided about prescriptions, she sees 
no reason why I cannot continue using the same, convenient, pharmacy that I am 
using now. Supervisor Wieder deserves credit for contacting people outside of 
her district in order to ensure accuracy. 
</P>
<P>
 In contrast, the supervisor for my district merely wrote me that old political 
standby: a good-doggie-down-Fido letter. These letters sound nice at first 
reading but, when examined more closely, are found to be lacking in information 
and/or assistance and/or interest in your viewpoints. 
</P>
<P>
 JUANITA MATASSA 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Ana 
</P>
<P>
 * In regard to Juanita Matassa's letter, "Health Plan Robs Poor of Dignity" 
(Nov. 20): 
</P>
<P>
 I took offense at the implication that only the poor have lost 
"self-determination" in regard to their health care. 
</P>
<P>
 I am a white, middle-class, college-educated, credentialed teacher, teaching 
in a private school. My employer offers a PPO or HMO through a major insurance 
carrier. Most of my co-workers and I cannot afford the luxury of the PPO. I 
have had four changes of plans in four years. A few weeks ago, my colleagues 
and I were given 24 hours' notice that most of our doctors had been dropped 
from our plan and we were assigned to yet another group of doctors we knew 
nothing about. 
</P>
<P>
 The poor, who benefit from the hard-earned tax dollars of people like myself, 
need to realize that they are not the only group that have no 
self-determination in their health care. Few of us do. 
</P>
<P>
 GLORIA STEELE 
</P>
<P>
 Mission Viejo 
</P>
</TEXT>
