<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL / SOUTHERN SECTION SEMIFINALS; NEWHALL CRUSHES QUARTZ 
HILL, 55-23 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNEDY COSGROVE and WILL ETHERIDGE and RICHARD GARDNER and CHRIS FOSTER and 
GEORGE ALFANO and DANA HADDAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Newhall Hart scored a touchdown on eight of its first nine possessions, 
including five in a row in the second quarter, to defeat Quartz Hill, 55-23, 
Saturday in a Southern Section Division II semifinal game at Quartz Hill. 
</P>
<P>
 Hart running back Ted Iacenda scored four touchdowns, giving him 40 this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians (13-0) rolled up 348 yards and six touchdowns in the first half, 
ending Quartz Hill's hopes of upsetting its third straight playoff opponent. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rebels finished 7-4-2. 
</P>
<P>
 Chino Hills Ayala 29, Diamond Bar 21 -- With Ayala trailing, 21-20, junior 
running back Jimmy Lejay scored on a 37-yard pass play from quarterback Steve 
Brinbaum to cap a nine play, 74-yard drive to give the Bulldogs (12-1) the lead 
for good. They play Sherman Oaks Notre Dame in the Division III final. 
</P>
<P>
 Brinbaum completed 10 of 19 passes for 215 yards and three touchdowns, and 
receiver Julius Taino caught six passes for 138 yards and two touchdowns for 
Ayala. 
</P>
<P>
 Diamond Bar (8-4) trailed early, 14-0, but got back into the game on the 
passing of senior quarterback Eric Stidham, who had two second-quarter 
touchdown passes, including a 59-yard play to receiver Lathiam Tyler. 
</P>
<P>
 Norco 20, Corona 0 -- Norco held Corona to nine yards of offense in the first 
half as it built a 20-0 lead in a Division IV semifinal at Corona High. 
</P>
<P>
 Andrew Whieldon threw two touchdown passes in the first half to lead Norco 
(11-2) to its second consecutive championship. Sean Hansen and Mike McCaskell 
led the Cougars' defense with two sacks each. 
</P>
<P>
 Corona, outgained on offense, 327 to 141, finished 9-3-1. 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim Servite 34, Lake Forest El Toro 19 -- David Bedard rushed for 168 
yards and three touchdowns and Frank Patti gained 105 yards in a Division V 
semifinal at Mission Viejo High. 
</P>
<P>
 Servite, which won back-to-back Division I titles in 1982-83, will play 
Newport Harbor on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the Friars' offense that got them to the final. They had scored only 19 
points in two playoff games but finally broke loose in the second half. They 
finished with 340 yards rushing. 
</P>
<P>
 Bedard scored on runs of two, 39 and 23 yards. His last touchdown, with 48 
seconds left, clinched the victory. 
</P>
<P>
 Servite's defense, which had three consecutive shutouts, was strong again in 
the first half. The Friars allowed only 62 yards in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
 Ontario Chaffey 21, Rancho Cucamonga 3 -- Joe Williams' 54-yard touchdown 
reception on a deflected pass in the first quarter was all the scoring Chaffey 
(12-1) needed in a Division VI semifinal at Chaffey College. 
</P>
<P>
 Chaffey, third-place finisher in the Mt. Baldy League, will play Atla Loma, 
Mt. Baldy League champion, for the divisional title Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Rancho Cucamonga finished 11-2. 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai Nordhoff 30, Santa Ynez 19 -- On first and 10 at the Ranger 12-yard line, 
running back Josh Hawkins broke through the left side of the line and took off 
on an 88-yard touchdown run in a Division IX semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
 The play was wiped out because of a holding call on Nordhoff, but Hawkins did 
the same thing two plays later to give the Rangers (10-3) a 16-0 lead before 
4,000 at Nordhoff. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Ynez finishes 11-2. KENNEDY COSGROVE and WILL ETHERIDGE and RICHARD 
GARDNER and CHRIS FOSTER and GEORGE ALFANO and DANA HADDAD 
</P>
