<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY SECTION FOOTBALL PLAYOFFS; BIRMINGHAM PUTS END TO WILSON'S COMEBACK, 
SEASON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SMITH, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After teammate and best friend Marvin Powell went down to injury, Courtney 
Blount took it upon himself to lead his Birmingham team to victory. 
</P>
<P>
 "When Marvin got hurt, that inspired us to play," said the Birmingham running 
back."I had to do it for Marvin because he would do it for me." 
</P>
<P>
 Blount rushed for 209 yards and three touchdowns in 21 carries as Birmingham 
topped Wilson, 27-20, in a City Section 4-A semifinal game at Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
 Powell suffered a mild concussion at 7:08 in the second quarter after being 
tackled by Wilson defensive back Jaime Munoz. Powell was taken to County-USC 
Medical Center.  
</P>
<P>
 After Blount scored his third touchdown of the game on a 14-yard run that put 
the Braves ahead, 27-13, with 11:09 remaining in the fourth quarter, Wilson 
fought back. 
</P>
<P>
 Mule quarterback Eddie Gonzales, who was 11 of 22 for 191 yards, connected 
with Luis Sanchez for his only touchdown of the game on a 40-yard pass to bring 
Wilson within 27-20 at the 8:16 mark. 
</P>
<P>
 After stopping Birmingham on downs, Wilson got the ball at its 48-yard line 
with .44 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 Gonzales drove the Mules to the Birmingham 15-yard line but his third-down 
pass to Sanchez was intercepted by defensive back Rick Courtney in the end 
zone. 
</P>
<P>
 "Birmingham is a really good football team," said Wilson coach Eddie Martinez. 
"We couldn't stop their running game." 
</P>
<P>
 Blount, who rushed for 148 yards in the first half, scored on runs of 19 and 1 
yard, the second of which put Birmingham ahead, 12-7. 
</P>
<P>
 Gonzales, who rushed for 27 yards in seven carries, scored on a one-yard run 
to give Wilson a 13-12 halftime lead. 
</P>
