<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOLISH PLEASURE, WINNER OF '75 KENTUCKY DERBY, DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Foolish Pleasure, winner of the 1975 Kentucky Derby, has died. The 22-year-old 
stallion died Nov. 17 at the Horseshoe Ranch near Dayton, where he had been 
living since September 1993, owner Ron Vanderhoef said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 He said Foolish Pleasure had been colicky and in discomfort that day and died 
about 6 p.m. during surgery for a ruptured stomach. 
</P>
<P>
 Foolish Pleasure was retired at the end of the 1976 racing season after 
winning the Suburban Handicap at Aqueduct in New York, the Donn Handicap at 
Gulfstream Park in Florida and the Arlington Invitational at Arlington Park in 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
 His most memorable race, however, was his 1975 match race against the filly 
Ruffian at Belmont Park. Ruffian fell during the race and later was destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
