<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUGE PAY JUMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regarding your story on the Thousand Oaks city manager's retroactive pay 
raise: he started in 1978 at $3,458 per month to his present $10,764. I guess 
he has something to be thankful for while we taxpayers are like the turkey that 
I just ate: helpless. 
</P>
<P>
 I wonder how many of your readers have been lucky enough to have a 311% 
increase in pay doing the same job. My wife is to be laid off before Christmas 
because the plant that employed 800 in Oxnard will make the widgets at a 
cheaper cost in Singapore. With a science degree and 20 years' work experience, 
companies want to offer her entry-level pay; why should they pay a premium when 
there are 100 applicants for every job offer? But alas, city bureaucratic 
bosses are different. The money is not coming out of their income or company 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
 NICK E. QUIDWAI 
</P>
<P>
 Newbury Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
