<HEADLINE>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES: L.A. SPEAK; FUNEREAL PHRASES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Janet Kinosian 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 bake and shake: v. to cremate a body and scatter the ashes. "It's going to be 
tough to bake and shake that guy; he must weigh 400 pounds." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 china: n. a plain wood coffin. Years ago, many Chinese laborers were buried in 
these. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 good and plenty: n. a container of cremated remains. When shaken, it sounds 
lke a box of Good and Plenty. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 in and out: n. a funeral home whose volume of cremations invites suspicions 
that it is burning more than one corpse at a time. "They have to be an in and 
out; no one can do that meny cremations in a day." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 slumber room: n. a room off a funeral parlor's main chapel where the loved one 
rests. Janet Kinosian 
</P>
